                     <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18330905-171-off946 t18330905-171-victim1634"></join>
                  </persName>
               
            .</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18330905-171-person1635">
                  JAMES 
                  ROZEE
               <interp inst="t18330905-171-person1635" type="surname" value="ROZEE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18330905-171-person1635" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18330905-171-person1635" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live in <placeName id="t18330905-171-crimeloc948">Great Pearl-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18330905-171-crimeloc948" type="placeName" value="Great Pearl-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18330905-171-crimeloc948" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18330905-171-off946 t18330905-171-crimeloc948"></join>, and am a <rs id="t18330905-171-viclabel949" type="occupation">weaver</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18330905-171-victim1634 t18330905-171-viclabel949"></join>. I had known the prisoner about five weeks; he worked in my shop - I was at work on this velvet, but on the 17th of July, I went out; I had eleven yards and a quarter in my loom - I left the prisoner there; he had velvet in his loom, the same as mine - I went out a little after ten o'clock, I returned a little after four; the prisoner was then gone, and his work and mine were both gone - the velvet in his loom was not mine, he had it from another master on his own account; I went directly and acquainted the two masters of it - Mr. Graham, of Spital-square is my employer - I had been that morning to Mrs. Simmons, to put up a loom for her - we have not heard of the velvet since; the prisoner did not return to my house; he was taken up the next day - my master gave me into custody as soon as I told him of the loss.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18330905-171-person1636">
                  FRANCES 
                  SIMMONS
               <interp inst="t18330905-171-person1636" type="surname" value="SIMMONS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18330905-171-person1636" type="given" value="FRANCES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18330905-171-person1636" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live in Catherine-wheel-alley, Bishopsgate. On the 17th of July, the prosecutor came, and was security for a loom for me, and he put it up - he left me about four o'clock in the afternoon; he returned about six, and said, he had been robbed - I had not seen the prisoner for a week or two before that, but that night I saw him with his sisters at the Blue Ball public-house, in Cock-lane - I looked at him a long while, because he was clean, and I had not seen him so before; I asked his sisters, if he was not their brother; they said, no - I then looked at his hand, and saw one finger was off, and I knew it was him - I flew out of the house to look for a policeman, and the prisoner escaped - the next morning I went to Mr. Sturgeon's; he went with me to a house in Castle-street - we went up stairs, and Sturgeon persuaded the prisoner to come down; there was a poker taken up, but I do not know whether the prisoner took it, or whether it was a pipe in his mouth - he ran after me into the passage.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18330905-171-person1637">
                  BENJAMIN 
                  LOCKWOOD
               <interp inst="t18330905-171-person1637" type="surname" value="LOCKWOOD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18330905-171-person1637" type="given" value="BENJAMIN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18330905-171-person1637" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I went with her to the house; I stood at the door; she went up, and came down screaming murder; the prisoner came down, made use of bad expressions, and asked, what we wanted with him - he walked with Sturgeon and me to Church-street, Bethnalgreen; we met the police, and give him in charge.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18330905-171-person1638">
                  MARY 
                  GHOST
               <interp inst="t18330905-171-person1638" type="surname" value="GHOST"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18330905-171-person1638" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18330905-171-person1638" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the wife of Richard Ghost; I live under the room in which this velvet was; the prosecutor went out a little after ten o'clock on the 17th of July, and asked me to give an eye to the door; after he had been gone a little while, the prisoner came down; he went out, and came back again with a strange man, and they went up stairs together - the strange man came down soon after, and the prisoner followed him with a bundle under his right arm, and a bag in his left; he said to me, "Would you give an eye to the door?" I said,"Yes"; they then went away past my window; the prisoner came back again, and went up stairs, and when he came down again, he said, "I do not think my work safe here, and when this is done, I shall have no more;" I saw no more of him; I saw no one else go in.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18330905-171-person1639">
                  WILLIAM 
                  BEDFORD
               <interp inst="t18330905-171-person1639" type="surname" value="BEDFORD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18330905-171-person1639" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18330905-171-person1639" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             (police-constable H 23). I took the prisoner, on the 18th of July - I searched him at the station-house; I found 9s. 6d. in silver on him, and 2d. in copper.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18330905-171-person1640">
                  CHARLES 
                  LEFEVRE
               <interp inst="t18330905-171-person1640" type="surname" value="LEFEVRE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18330905-171-person1640" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18330905-171-person1640" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I worked in Rozee's shop with the prisoner, on the 15th of July, from morning till night - he went out in the morning to get some tobacco; he was a long while gone, and when he came back, he said, he had been to his sister's to borrow 1d. to buy the tobacco; he then had his dinner, smoked his pipe, and worked till eight o'clock at night.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence (written). I had my work from Mr. Green, of Steward-street, which I took to Mr. Rozee, who engaged to learn me to make velvet; at length I found he was not a trust-worthy person, being in the habit of getting drunk for three or four weeks at a time; I heard that he had lived with a female for some years, until she was committed to Newgate for robbing the person's house who had engaged her to wash and char; he then sent the children to the workhouse, and left her till she was married to a Mr. Simmons: and now Mr. and Mrs. Simmons, Mr. Rozee, and the children all live in one room. On the day named in the indictment, a young man came to pay me some money, which he had borrowed at sundry times; we staid a short time; when we came down stairs I had my dirty linen, and the young man's dirty linen, to take to my sisters to wash; the door of the workshop has no fastening, and as I came down stairs, I said to Mrs. Ghost, "Be so good as to look after the door, as Rozee is out getting drunk again;" I then left the young man, and went home to my sister's to dinner. The street-door is always open, so that any person might go up or down the stairs without being perceived; and Mr. Rozee some time ago lost his work before, while he was out at the public-house.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18330905-171-person1641">
                  George 
                  Hughes
               <interp inst="t18330905-171-person1641" type="surname" value="Hughes"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18330905-171-person1641" type="given" value="George"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18330905-171-person1641" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             gave the prisoner a good character.</p>
